Hey Akhil,

This actually was discussed on the issue. The claim was that in order to be truly backwards compatible with pervious versions of Go, we needed to be able to decode the potentially base64 encoded byte arrays that theoretically may be have serialized in current and previous versions of Go. I don't know of any other way to do that besides using the base64 package (or copy and pasting from the base64 package). It seems we're stuck between two requirements here. Which would you prefer I go with? Or is there a third option?

$ go test runtime -count=1
ok  	runtime	157.900s
go test runtime -count=1  202.21s user 8.40s system 132% cpu 2:39.17 total 

$ ../bin/go test -count=1 ./runtime/runtime-gdb_test.go
ok  	command-line-arguments	1.692s
../bin/go test -count=1 ./runtime/runtime-gdb_test.go  4.61s user 0.96s system 275% cpu 2.018 total

No runtime errors no, but then there appears to have been no errors before either so are you thinking of something in particular that I might have missed?!

What WAS revealed by the tests however, was that the test binary's 'sliceval' string, coming out of an 'info locals' call, went from:

        slicevar = {array = 0xc000094000, len = 4990053, cap = 3}

e.g. the default printer fallback (note the nonsense 'len' value) to now being matched but printed as:

        slicevar = []string

This 'issue' harks all the way back to:

commit fb2706113f36452f7e1e514be1949c0cdae46835
Author: Luuk van Dijk <lvd@golang.org>
Date:   Wed Feb 29 16:42:25 2012 +0100

    pkg/runtime: 2 sanity checks in the runtime-gdb.py prettyprinters.
    
    Don't try to print obviously corrupt slices or interfaces.
    Doesn't actually solve 3047 or 2818, but seems a good idea anyway.
    
    R=rsc, bsiegert
    CC=golang-dev
    https://golang.org/cl/5708061


..where 'Don't try to print obviously corrupt slices or interfaces.' translates to:

+               if self.val["len"] > self.val["cap"]:
+                       return

..but I think 'corrupt' is probably the wrong word here, as I imagine that it's ultimately due to the problem of missing (optimised) struct member symbols integral to the usability of the 'high-level' array ('slice').

So what's the best we can do given this is governed by missing symbols and thus optimisation?

The (dangerous) fallback?

      slicevar = {array = 0xc000094000, len = 4990053, cap = 3}

The (near useless) 'fixed' SliceTypePrinter?

      slicevar = []string

..or some compromise?

      slicevar = []string = {array = 0xc000094000, | no safe print, missing (optimised) symbols?}

Some useful words like this might give people a hint of what can be done to remedy the lack of printed content, no? Certainly the u/l array pointer/address needs printing (requiring further changes) as the data is definitely there, the user will just have to bravely poke at it manually.

Another question that springs to mind (for these tests at least), is 'why are we using an optimised test binary?' Platform differences? I've never expected anything but pain and ultimate capitulation from attempting to use gdb to debug an optimised binary, so why not add the -gcflags=all='-N' build switch in the test file?

The columns in the two rows above are ratios and refer respectively to the case when len(z) == len(x) == 0, the case when len(z) != 0 && s != 0, the case when len(z) != 0 && s == 0 && z.base != x.base, the case when len(z) != 0 && s == 0 && z.base == x.base.

Data for shrVU: 1 3029745 31 1659777


I did not investigate more deeply the usage patterns of shlVU and shrVU, but presumably in some cases shlVU and shrVU would be called with zero shift more often ... ?

> I think this package is basically frozen, in favor of the cryptobyte package.

I'm not sure I understand what the motivation here is.  There is an "encodings" module that contains various de/serialization mechanisms.  It seems entirely consistent to have a general use case asn1 package in there for de/serializing data to/from ASN.1.

Compared to the ASN.1 implementation that's bundled with crypto, I would expect that the encoding/asn1 package be much more applicable to general use cases while the crypto implementation would specifically support only the design goals of the crypto package, it's corner cases and nothing else.  

In fact, I would even go so far as to expect that proposals extending the functionality of the ASN1 package within crypto, in a way that was not required by crypto, would be rejected.  Why complicate a package beyond its purpose.

If the strategic intention is to consolidate onto a single ASN.1 library, then wouldn't it make more sense to deprecate the crypto implementation, and refactor crypto to leverage encoding/asn1.  

In addition, having looked at the cryptobyte doc, it looks far less friendly and/or scalable to use in general use cases with large and dynamic data structures compared to encodings/asn1.  The included examples are based on very simple data structures, and yet much harder to read than examples of encoding/asn1 that use bigger structures (IMO).

Patch Set 7:

The go/build package doesn't completely ignore all testdata directories. In fact, it only ignores testdata in local imports and vendor directory. In the latter case, testdata is only ignored when it is in the middle of the path. When testdata gets ignored, rather than explicitly returning an error, go/build returns an incomplete package information without any error, leaving its callers to guess how to deal with such incompleteness. In the case of #24854, unfortunately, it only errors out two hops down the import graph when the testdata imports a vendor package which in turn imports something else, making the error message sound meaningless.

The current implementation allows most package developers to write and use code in testdata without problems, which only occur in some non-obvious cases.

So the CL is inconsistent with what you expect go tool to work, but it is consistent with what go/build package is doing. Completely ignoring testdata may fail many tests and third party libraries.

One example I've seen is to define public/private keys as Go constants in testdata package and import that package whenever they are needed. Do you want to disallow such usage?
